{{short description|Radio galaxy and merger remnant}} {{Infobox Galaxy |name = [[Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies|Arp]] 187 |epoch = [[J2000]] |constellation name = [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]] |type = Radio Galaxy <ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for Arp 187 | url=http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/objsearch?objname=arp+187 | accessdate=2006-10-26 }}</ref> |appmag_v = 15,3 <ref name="ned" /> |size_v = 0',8 x 0',6 <ref name="ned" /> |z = 12095 ± 45 km/s <ref name="ned" /> |ra = {{RA|5|03|53}} <ref name="ned" /> |dec = {{DEC|-10|14|51}} <ref name="ned" /> |names = [[Principal Galaxies Catalogue|PGC]] 16691 <ref name="ned" /> }}
'''Arp 187''' is a [[radio galaxy]] and [[galaxy merger|merger remnant]] located in the [[constellation]] [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]]. It is an interacting galaxy pair (MCG-02-13-040).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-basic?Ident=arp+187+&submit=SIMBAD+search |title=Simbad |accessdate=2010-01-06}}</ref> It is included in the [[Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies]] in the category galaxies with narrow filaments.
The galaxy has two prominent radio lobes, however the emission of its [[Active galactic nucleus|AGN]] in [[X-ray]] is low, and so is the thermal output of the AGN torus as observed in [[infrared]], suggesting that it has been quenched. The detection of a narrow line region (with dimensions up to 10 kpc) with still active emission mean that the AGN was still active up to at least 10<sup>4-5</sup> years ago. In the nucleus of Arp 187 is predicted to lie a [[supermassive black hole]] with estimated mass around 6.7 × 10<sup>8</sup> {{solar mass|link=yes}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ichikawa |first1=Kohei |last2=Ueda |first2=Junko |last3=Shidatsu |first3=Megumi |last4=Kawamuro |first4=Taiki |last5=Matsuoka |first5=Kenta |title=Signs of active galactic nucleus quenching in a merger remnant with radio jets |journal=Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan |date=1 February 2016 |volume=68 |issue=1 |pages=9 |doi=10.1093/pasj/psv112}}</ref>
