{{Infobox person | name = Cynthia Margaret Pine | image =Cynthis_Pine.jpg | image_size = | caption = Cynthia Pine in 2009 | birth_name = | birth_date = October 1953 | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] }} Professor '''Cynthia Pine''' [[CBE]] (born October, 1953) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] Dentistry educator. In 2003, she became the first woman to lead a British school of dentistry. She is the first woman appointed to head a dentistry school in the UK.<ref name="do" />
She is one of a group of highly successful Guyanese people in Britain ([[Michael White (journalist)|Michael White]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' refers to them as the "Guyanese mafia"), which includes [[Waheed Alli, Baron Alli|Waheed Alli]], [[Raj Persaud]], [[Herman Ouseley]] and [[David Dabydeen]], [[Keith Waithe]] and [[Rudolph Dunbar]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Guyanese Achievers UK|last=Vidur|first=Dindayal|publisher=|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>
==Life== Pine was born in 1953 in [[Guyana]].<ref name="yudu" /> She graduated The University of Manchester with a Bachelor of Dental Surgery (BDS) in 1976 and a PhD from the same institution in 1982, and has an MBA from the University of Dundee.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|date=2007-12-01|title=Pine, Prof. Cynthia Margaret, (born 2 Oct. 1953), Professor of Dental Public Health, since 2013, and Academic Lead and Head, Unit of Dental Public Health, since 2014, Institute of Dentistry, Barts and The London, Queen Mary University of London; Consultant in Dental Public Health, Salford Royal NHS Foundation Trust, since 2013; Managing Director, Kippax Design Ltd, since 2013|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-245351|journal=Who's Who|language=en|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.245351}}</ref>
She was appointed Dean of the [[University of Liverpool School of Dentistry]] in 2003. She was later appointed as Pro Vice Chancellor, International at [[Salford University]].<ref name="yudu">[http://content.yudu.com/A1zgh3/PowerList2013/resources/59.htm Cynthia Pine], Power List 2013, Retrieved 24 November 2015</ref>
Since 2013 Pine has been a Professor of Dental Public Health at the Institute of Dentistry, [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]], and Academic Lead and Head of the Unit of Dental Public Health since 2014.<ref name=":0" />
Pine was made a Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE) in 2006.<ref name=do>[http://www.dentistry.qmul.ac.uk/staff/professorcynthiapine.html Cynthia Pine], Barts and London School of Dentistry, Retrieved 25 November 2015</ref> Pine has been included in the Powerlist of the UK’s 100 most influential people of African and Afro-Caribbean descent.<ref name=yudu/>
