'''Derek Lee''' (also known as '''Derek E. Lee''' or '''Derek Edward Lee''') is an [[Americans|American]] [[Ecology|ecologist]] and [[wildlife biologist]] specializing in [[population biology]] and [[conservation biology]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theawl.com/2013/03/quit-your-job-living-with-the-wild-things-without-compromise/|title=Quit Your Job! Living With the Wild Things, Without Compromise|work=The Awl|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en}}</ref> Lee was born in [[Lodi, California|Lodi]], California on March 15, 1971, and attended [[Tokay High School]]. Lee earned his bachelor's degree from the [[University of California, Santa Barbara|University of California at Santa Barbara]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucsbalum.com/newsevents/news/dlee|title=Alumni Spotlight: Derek Lee|website=ucsbalum.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> his master's degree from [[Humboldt State University]], and his Ph.D. from [[Dartmouth College]]. For his MS degree he investigated the migratory behavior of [[black brant]] geese in [[Humboldt Bay]] using [[Mark and recapture|capture-recapture]] statistics to estimate stopover duration and space use. For his Ph.D., he studied the spatial [[demography]] of [[Giraffe|giraffes]] in the [[Tarangire Ecosystem|Tarangire ecosystem]] of [[Tanzania]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/06/surge-wildlife-killings-wiping-out-giraffes|title=Surge in wildlife killings is wiping out giraffes|date=2017-06-21|work=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wbur.org/onpoint/2017/03/08/giraffe-extinction-endanger|title=Where Have All The Giraffes Gone?|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> His academic work on climate influences on marine bird demography, spotted owls and forest fire, and computer vision applications to wildlife biology are highly cited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.ch/citations?user=35An-xcAAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao|title=Derek E. Lee - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.ch|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> His discovery of a white leucistic giraffe was widely reported in popular media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/01/27/africa/white-giraffe-omo-leucistic/index.html|title=Omo, the rare white giraffe, is in danger - CNN|last=CNN|first=Esra Gurkan, for|work=CNN|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/rare-white-giraffe-spotted-tanzania-420282|title=Rare white giraffe spotted in Tanzania|date=2016-01-27|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2014/06/17/safeguarding-giraffe-populations-from-extinction-in-east-africa/|title=Safeguarding Giraffe Populations From Extinction in East Africa – National Geographic Blog|website=blog.nationalgeographic.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> 

He worked at [[Point Blue Conservation Science]] for 8 years on [[Farallon Islands|Southeast Farallon Island]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/science/article/FOCUS-ON-CLIMATE-CHANGE-A-rocky-laboratory-of-2647720.php|title=FOCUS ON CLIMATE CHANGE / A rocky laboratory of ecosystem science / FARALLON ISLANDS: Researchers study how warmer waters impact marine life habits|work=SFGate|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> studying how ocean climate change affects the population dynamics of marine predators such as [[Elephant seal|elephant seals]], [[Cassin's auklet|Cassin's auklets]], and [[Common murre|common murres]]. He is founder and CEO of [http://www.wildnatureinstitute.org/ Wild Nature Institute], a research organization. Since 2018 he has also worked at [[Pennsylvania State University]] as an Associate Research Professor. 

Lee has published more than 35 scientific peer-reviewed papers in the field of ecology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1042-9543|title=Derek E. Lee (0000-0002-1042-9543) - ORCID {{!}} Connecting Research and Researchers|last=ORCID|website=orcid.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> mainly focused on demography and population biology of wild vertebrates.

