{{Taxobox | regnum = [[Bacterium|Bacteria]] | phylum = [[Acidobacteria]] | classis = [[Acidobacteria]] | ordo = [[Acidobacteriales]] | familia = [[Acidobacteriaceae]] | genus = '''''Telmatobacter''''' | genus_authority = Pankratov & Dedysh, 2011 | species = '''''T. bradus''''' | binomial = ''Telmatobacter bradus'' | binomial_authority = Pankratov & Dedysh, 2011 }}
'''''Telmatobacter''''' is a genus of [[bacteria]] in the family [[Acidobacteriaceae]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Pankratov | first1 = T. A. | last2 = Kirsanova | first2 = L. A. | last3 = Kaparullina | first3 = E. N. | last4 = Kevbrin | first4 = V. V. | last5 = Dedysh | first5 = S. N. | title = ''Telmatobacter bradus'' gen. nov., sp. nov., a cellulolytic facultative anaerobe from subdivision 1 of the Acidobacteria and emended description of Acidobacterium capsulatum Kishimoto et al. 1991 | doi = 10.1099/ijs.0.029629-0 | journal = International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology | year = 2011 | pmid = 21460138| pmc = | volume=62 | issue = Pt 2 | pages=430–437}}</ref>
==History== ''Telmatobacter'' was first described in 2011. The name derives from the Greek noun telma–atos, meaning swamp or bog, and the noun bacter meaning short rod.
==Description== ''Telmatobacter'' is a genus of [[Gram-negative bacteria]]. They appear as motile, single [[bacillus (shape)|rods]]. ''Telmatobacter'' reproduce by normal [[cell division]] and do not form spores. They are [[Facultative anaerobic organism|facultative anaerobes]] as well as [[Primary nutritional groups#Energy and carbon|chemo-organotrophs]]. They prefer to grow with [[sugar]]s and [[pectin]] as growth substrates, although they are capable of fermenting sugars and several [[polysaccharide]]s, including crystalline [[cellulose]]. They [[Acidophile|prefer acidic]] conditions and [[mesophile|moderate temperatures]], and they grow better on liquid medium than solid agar medium. Unlike some other bacteria, ''Telmatobacter'' do not produce [[hydrogen sulfide|hydrogen sulfide gas]] from [[thiosulfate]], nor [[indole]] from [[tryptophan]]. [[Sodium chloride|Salt]] inhibits growth at concentrations above 0.1% (w/v). The DNA [[GC-content|G+C content]] is 57.6%. ''Telmatobacter'' are found in acidic wetlands, specifically [[Sphagnum]] peat bogs. The only and type species is ''Telmatobacter bradus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bacterio.net/telmatobacter.html |accessdate=27 September 2016 |publisher=LPSN bacterio.net |title=Telmatobacter}}</ref>
